properties.documentation: Truth value with one of two possible values: true or false.
Sequence of bytes used to transmit binary data.

Negative or positive, dimensionless number with decimal representation to allow representation of non-integer values. In theory, floating point values have a range from (-inf, inf) but in practice, due to a particular representation, this range may be limited. All floating point representations should be able to represent both positive and negative infinity.

Dimensionless, negative or positive whole number or zero. For the purposes of ISA, generic integers are required to hold value in the range (-2^32, 2^32). Specializations of the integer, as defined in the Simple Types, may be able to hold values in the range [0, 2^64), but values in this range are not generally needed in practice.
UTF-8 encoded ASCII text. The specifics of how a string is encoded are encoding-specific, and the ISA Data Model treats that string as a whole without regard for its individual elements.

This is a special type that represents any type defined in the Data Model. This type is typically used in conjunction with a field that identifies the type of data that should be expected, such as in a Name-Value Pair.
Uniquely identifies an Administrative message of type ALARM. Reserved for Future Use.
SI unit for electric current.
A wrapper needed when using a boolean as part of the filtering logic.
SI-derived unit of radioactivity.
Quantity of radioactive substance deposited per unit area.
Quantity of radioactive substance in a unit volume.
A string identifying a unique battle space object.
Temperature measurement in degrees Celsius.
A logarithmic unit used to express the ratio of two values of a physical quantity, often power or intensity. (Definition from Wikipedia)
The power ratio in decibels of the measured power reference to one milliwatt.
Magnitude of an angular velocity in a single angular dimension in floating point degrees per second. The specific reference frame of the value is dictated by the context in which the value occurs.
Angular distance between two rays sharing a common endpoint. All angles are represented in floating point degrees.

Every event generated by a component must provide an integer key that allows that event to be updated and referred to at a later point. Event IDs are required to be unique only within the component that's generating them and within a reasonable timeframe after the event is generated. Event IDs are not expected to be sufficient to uniquely identify a single event throughout all time. For this purpose, the combination of source component ID, timestamp, and event ID are used.
SI-derived unit of absorbed dose, specific energy, and kerma.
Gray per second
Used to express a frequency.
Unit for expressing energy or work.
Mass of an object in kilograms.
Mass of a substance contained within a given area. Expressed in floating point kilograms per square meter (kg / m^2).
Instantaneous concentration of mass within a volume of space. Expressed in floating point kilograms per cubic meter (kg/m^3).
Product of a mass concentration and the exposure (integration) time. These are always expressed in floating point kilogram-seconds per cubic meter (kg-s / m^3).
The number of bits exchanged per second. The value 10 translate to 10,000,000 bits per second.
Linear distance between two points in a single dimension as a floating point value in meters.
Rate of change of distance per unit time in a single dimension in meters per second.
Force per unit area in pascals (newtons per square meter). 100 pascals = 1 hectopascal = 1 millibar.
Floating point value representing the percent of a value relative to a maximum.
Number of "parts" by weight of a substance per million parts of water. Mass fraction concentrations are always expressed in floating point parts per million (ppm).
Number of particles present within a given area. Particle deposition concentrations are always expressed in floating point particles per square meter (m^-2).
Concentration of measurable particles within a volume of space. Particle concentrations are always expressed in floating point particles per cubic meter. (m^-3).
Priority level for a message, with 0 being of the utmost importance and higher numbers less so.
Interval, in floating point seconds, between two points in time. Representations of intervals must have millisecond resolution.

Symbol Identification Coding Scheme (SIDC) is a 15-character alphanumeric identifier that provides the information necessary to display or transmit a tactical symbol between MIL-STD-2525 compliant systems.

Universal Component Identifier. This is a string that uniquely identifies a specific component. This is the string that will always be used to refer to this specific component. This can be an assigned number from a logistics group (such as the Army's URNs) or can be a vendor-assigned string (such as combining the manufacturer, model, and serial number in a unique way).

Uniform Resource Locator (URL) is a string used to specify where a resource is located on a network and the mechanism for retrieving it. URLs must comply with IETF RFC 1738, which governs the proper form and syntax of the URL.
SI unit for electric potential.
Unit for expressing power.
Unit for describing irradiance
Devices that are capable of detecting specific biological materials.
Devices or instruments that determine the detectable presence, concentration, or quantity of a given analyte.
A device that can produce accurate orientation information.
Capabilities that deal with electrical systems, incuding producers and consumers of electricity
Capabilities and properties of devices that can detect the location (and possibly other information) of entities. These devices include RADARs, UGS, etc.
Optional general purpose capabilities of components.
Devices capable of modifying their own orientation.
A device capable of providing visible or infrared illumination
Devices that capture live imagery from a particular viewpoint.
Devices capable of emiting light through optical amplification.
Capabilites that allow for the fulfillment of data subscriptions.
A device that can produce accurate and absolute location information for itself.
Components capable of storing media and serving it via URLs.
Devices capable of reporting on the atmosphere (including weather).
A device that is able to move to different geographic locations.
Devices that use radio waves to determine the range, altitude, direction, or speed of objects.
Devices that use wireless means to communication
Devices with ability to detect, track, and/or identify high-energy particles such as those produced by nuclear decay, cosmic radiation, or reactions in a particle accelerator.
Capabilities typical of devices that can measure distance via line of sight.
Capabilities that are recommended for all components.
Capabilities that are required in all components.
Capabilities related to preventing accidental damage.
Capabilities that are related to securing a sensor against hostile use.
Devices capable of target designation.
Absolute position or geographic area of the detection.
The measured atmospheric humidity at the detection position of the event; or if not present, the position of the detector.
The measured atmospheric pressure at the detection position of the event; or if not present, the position of the detector.
The measured atmospheric temperature at the detection position of the event; or if not present, the position of the detector.
The measured atmospheric wind at the detection position of the event, or if not present, the position of the detector.
Orientation of the detection.
Biological reading.
A confirmed or suspected entity on the battlefield which is identified using a unique ID.
Chemical reading.
Human readable command about the observation
Relative position of the detection.
Standard identity of the observed entity (if applicable).
Resources (such as video, audio, images, etc.) related to the observation.
The primary method used to generate this event. Suggested options include: "MANUAL", "ATR_V", "ATR_T", "MAGNETIC", "ACOUSTIC", "FUSION", "RADAR", and "LIDAR".
Position of the detection.
Radiation reading.
The human readable reason that the event referenced in the SER is being recalled.
The human readable reason that the referenced event is being resolved.
The measured solar radiation at the detection position of the event; or if not present, the position of the detector.
Velocity of the detection.
Name of the personnel who have verified that the MIL-STD-2525 in the event is 100% correct.
AC current being consumed by the load.
AC current being produced by the source.
AC voltage used by the load.
AC voltage provided by the source
When true, this property indicates the device is actively performing it's responsibilities
Current arming state of the component. The presence of this property within a component indicates that the component needs to be armed before an active command can be invoked
The orientation of the component related to the parent platform.
The position of the component related to the parent platform.
Whether an imager's automatic brightness capability is enabled
Whether an imager's automatic contrast capability is enabled.
Whether an imager's automatic focus capability is enabled.
Whether the capability of automatic adjustment to a signal gain is enabled
Whether the capability of automatic level adjustment to pixel values is enabled.
Whether the capability of automatic scanning is enabled.
The current brightness level.
The results of the last Built-in-test that was run.

Current camera mode of the component. This is mutable only if the camera has more than one supported camera mode. The camera mode gives a rough indication of the frequency range of the camera, indicating its suitability for operation in different environments. If a single camera supports more than one mode, then it's assumed that a switch needs to be made between the modes. Any single device that supports more than one mode simultaneously should be modeled as one component for each mode.
Configuration version for this specific component. This is analogous to a software release number for the component.
Whether a component is charged.
Current camera contrast as a percentage of maximum.
Crypto key filled
Data being received by the component.
Data being sent by the component. This property is for data that is being transmitted, not for data that is available. To list data that is available for a client to fetch use the Resources property.
DC current being consumed by the load.
DC current being produced by the source.
DC voltage used by the load.
DC voltage provided by the source.
When true, this property indicates the device is allowed to become active.
Minimum eye safe distance from the device.
Current field of regard for the camera or component that has a field of regard; it is the total view over the scan time.
Current field of view for the camera or component that has a field of view; it is the instantaneous view.
Current focus level of the component.
Frame rate for video produced by a camera.
Set of frequencies being used by an emitting component such as Radar, laser designator, or other component
The ground intercept is the geographic position where the component pointing vector intercepts the ground.
The version of the hardware being used by the component.
Key aspects of the component using MIL-STD-2525 nomenclature.
Current size of the iris as a percentage of maximum.
No documentation - type = percent
No documentation - type = Db
The current state of a network interface. True indicates the interface is up, false indicates the interfaces is down.

The orientation of the component within its own local reference frame. In the case of a gimbal this property is used to report the difference between the gimbal head's current orientation and the gimbal head's home orientation.
The position of the component within its own local reference frame.
The individual or group to contact when maintenance is necessary.
Component manufacturer, producer, or vendor.
The manufacturer of the component. For backwards compatibility, users should also provide the Manufacturer property.
The maximum time interval that will elapse between two subsequent sends of a components status

The minimum time interval that must occur between the sending of two subsequent component statuses. Any state changes occurring during the interval must be cached and sent during the next allowed time.
Model of this component within the manufacturer's product line.
A user friendly name for the component. This can be reassigned or changed as needed.
Current operating state of the component. This is a reflection of the state of the component itself and not the ISA lifecycle state that the component is in.

Absolute orientation with respect to the reference frame defined by the y axis pointing to true north, the Z axis pointing perpendicular to the WGS-84 reference spheroid at that point, and the X axis pointing east.
The owner of this specific component.

Property to be used to report the position from hardware when the Position property is being overridden using the Position Override property. This property is optional and is not required when providing the override capability.
Color palette used to visualize thermal energy.
Current position of the component.
Property to be used to override a perceived position from hardware.
For devices that support variable power, represents the given percentage of the maximum available power.
The current state of power to the component
The program of record of the component.
Interval between a laser's pulses.
The quality of the output produced by the component.
Current radar mode of the component.
The expected usable range of the component.
The current receiving data rate of the component.
The strength of the received signal.
Physical relationship between this device and other devices. Useful for determining the absolute position or orientation of a device that may be mounted to another platform.
Current capacity of energy reserve in percent of maximum capacity. This is can be used to report a fuel tank capability or battery level.
The resolution of the output produced by the component. (Himelo)
Accessible resources for obtaining media (streams or otherwise) generated by this component.
The number of satellites in use.
Time it takes for a scanning device to fully cover its scan area one time
Unique number assigned to this component within the manufacturer's model line. The triplet (manufacturer, model, serial number) is expected to be globally and universally unique.
Contains the number of times the laser has been used.
No documentation - type = Db
The version of the software running on the component.
ISA specification version with which this component complies.
The individual or group to contact when non-maintenance support is needed.
Time to empty based on expected usage.
The current transmitting data rate of the component.
The strength of the produced signal.
Absolute velocity of the device
The area that is currently in view. For example, the physical area a camera is able to view.
No documentation
The wavelengths used by the laser

Full ordered list of inclusion and exclusion areas from the component. The ordering of the list allows for the nesting inclusion and exclusion zones to provide very detailed control over areas the component will include and exclude.
Current zoom level of the camera as a percentage of its maximum zoom.
